The '''[[Baharna]] in Kuwait''' ({{lang-ar|البحارنة في الكويت}}) migrated from their home country of [[Bahrain]] to Kuwait in the second half of the 18th century due to commercial opportunities or persecution or political instability in the Al Khalifa sheikhdom.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yczrAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA72|editor1=Steffen Hertog|editor2=Giacomo Luciani|editor3=Marc Valeri|title=Business Politics in the Middle East|publisher=[[C. Hurst & Co.]]|page=72|isbn=978-1-84904-235-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC&pg=PA47|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|author=Laurence Louër|publisher=C. Hurst & Co.|year=2011|page=47}}</ref> The Baharna of Kuwait were typically shipbuilders, lived in their own quarter (farig il-baharna), although not segregated and were not prohibited from living elsewhere. The quarter itself was not exclusively Baharna either.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.bh/books?id=aWRJAAAAYAAJ&q=Baharna+kuwait|author=Clive Holes|title=Dialect, Culture, and Society in Eastern Arabia: Ethnographic texts|publisher=Brill|year=2001|pages=347}}</ref> and together with Hasawi and Iranian Shia, constituted 15,000 out of 50,000 [[Kuwait City|Kuwait Town]] inhabitants in 1918 (30% of the total population).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uHl_CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA75|author=Farah Al-Nakib|title=Kuwait Transformed: A History of Oil and Urban Life|publisher=[[Stanford University Press]]|year=2016|page=75|lccn=2015048590|isbn=9780804796392}}</ref> 

The 18th century [[Germans|German]] explorer [[Carsten Niebuhr]] visited [[Failaka Island]] in 1765 and found that a disproportionate amount of its inhabitants were Baharna and whom worked as [[Pearl hunting|pearl divers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bahrainhistory.net/1536.html|title=هجرة البحارنة إلى الكويت ونشأة صناعة السفن|date=27 October 2014|accessdate=2 July 2018}}</ref>

