{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Neil Casey | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth-date and age|July 28, 1981|July 28, 1981}} | birth_place = [[Wilmington, Delaware]], US | nationality = American | occupation = Actor, comedian, television writer, theatre director, playwright | years_active = 2005–present | notable_works = ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' }}
'''Neil Casey''' (born July 28, 1981) is an American actor, comedian, television writer, theatre director and playwright best known for his work as a writer on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' and ''[[Inside Amy Schumer]]''. He was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series|Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series]] both in 2013 for writing on ''SNL'' and in 2014 for ''Inside Amy Schumer''. In 2016 he played the villain, Rowan North in the film ''[[Ghostbusters (2016 film)|Ghostbusters]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-ghostbusters-reboot-casts-neil-casey-as-villain-20150707-story.html|title='Ghostbusters' reboot casts 'SNL' alum Neil Casey as villain|last=Gettell|first=Oliver|date=July 7, 2015|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2016-07-22}}</ref> He also co-starred in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[Making History (TV series)|Making History]]''.
== Career == Casey graduated from the [[University of Delaware]] with a B.A. in English, including a concentration in drama and minoring in Theatre.<ref name="April2015DO" /><ref name=UCBComedy>{{cite web|title=Neil Casey's profile by UCB Theatre|url=http://ucbcomedy.com/user/300|publisher=ucbcomedy.com|accessdate=July 16, 2015}}</ref> He started his career in theatre in 2001 and worked at [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theatre|UCB Theatre]], where he has also taught since 2007. He directed, wrote, and acted in several shows at the theatre.<ref name="UCBComedy" />
=== Acting career === In 2015, Casey starred in the Yahoo! Screen series ''[[Other Space]]'', created by [[Paul Feig]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://slapdashfestival.co.uk/projects/anthony-atamanuik-neil-casey-sunday-7-thursday-11-june/|title=Anthony Atamanuik & Neil Casey workshops|date=June 11, 2015|work=slapdashfestival.co.uk|accessdate=July 16, 2015}}</ref>
In July 2015, Casey was cast in his first breakthrough film, ''[[Ghostbusters (2016 film)|Ghostbusters]]'', the reboot of the [[Ghostbusters|1984 film]], playing a villain named Rowan.<ref name="GhostbustersCast">{{cite news|last1=Hipes|first1=Patrick|title='Ghostbusters' Reboot Finds Its Bad Guy: Neil Casey|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/ghostbusters-3-neil-casey-cast-villain-1201471580/|accessdate=July 11, 2015|work=deadline.com|date=July 7, 2015}}</ref> The film was shot in [[Boston]], directed by Paul Feig, and stars [[Kristen Wiig]], [[Melissa McCarthy]], [[Kate McKinnon]], and [[Leslie Jones (comedian)|Leslie Jones]] in the lead roles. ''Ghostbusters'' was released on July 15, 2016 by [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Sony Dates 16 Films Including Two More ‘Bad Boys’ Sequels, ‘Jumanji’ Remake|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sony-films-bad-boys-jennifer-lawrence-passengers-1201557242/|accessdate=September 21, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 5, 2015}}</ref>
In 2017, Casey began co-starring opposite [[Adam Pally]] in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] time-travel comedy ''[[Making History (TV series)|Making History]]''; he played the role of [[Samuel Adams|Sam Adams]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/making-history-casts-john-hancock-900665|title='Making History' Casts Its John Hancock, Sam Adams (Exclusive)|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=June 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2017-05-16|language=en}}</ref>
=== Writing career === In 2012, Casey was hired to write [[Sketch comedy|comedy sketches]] for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'s'' [[Saturday Night Live (season 38)|season 38]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frucci|first1=Adam|title=UCB's Neil Casey Hired as a Writer at 'SNL'|url=http://splitsider.com/2012/09/ucbs-neil-casey-hired-as-a-writer-at-snl/|accessdate=July 15, 2015|work=splitsider.com|date=September 6, 2012}}</ref> He was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series|Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series]] at the [[65th Primetime Emmy Awards|65th show]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=65th Primetime Emmys Nominees and Winners|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2013?page=1|publisher=emmys.com|accessdate=July 16, 2015}}</ref> He was also nominated for a [[Writers Guild of America Award]] in [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2013|2013]] and 2015 in the category of Comedy/Variety (including talk) series.<ref name=PreviousWGA>{{cite web|title=Previous Nominees & Winners|url=http://www.wga.org/wga-awards/previous-nominees-winners.aspx|publisher=wga.org|accessdate=July 16, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512181500/http://www.wga.org/wga-awards/previous-nominees-winners.aspx|archivedate=May 12, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Nominees & Winners|url=http://www.wga.org/wga-awards/nominees-winners.aspx|publisher=wga.org|accessdate=July 16, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901174238/http://www.wga.org/wga-awards/nominees-winners.aspx|archivedate=September 1, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
In 2014, Casey was nominated for a Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series at the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards|66th show]] for his work on ''[[Inside Amy Schumer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=66th Primetime Emmys Nominees and Winners|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2014?page=1|publisher=emmys.com|accessdate=July 16, 2015}}</ref> He was also nominated for a Writers Guild of America Award in [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2014|2014]] in the category of Comedy/Variety (including talk) series.<ref name="PreviousWGA" />
In 2015, Casey wrote for the third season of ''[[Kroll Show]]''.<ref name=April2015DO>{{cite news|last1=Cormier|first1=Ryan|title=Wilmington's Neil Casey: From 'SNL' to 'Other Space'|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/story/pulpculture/2015/04/24/neil-casey/26295607/|accessdate=July 16, 2015|work=delawareonline.com|date=April 24, 2015}}</ref>
